                <head>No. 364.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bell</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Bayard</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1886-08-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 18, 1886</date>. (Received August
                        31.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 166.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that I have recently
                    learned from sources which may be considered as authoritative that the recent
                    surveys in the islands of Java and Sumatra have brought to light the existence
                    of petroleum wells of apparent considerable value.</p>
                <p>In order to fully explore and to ascertain the approved system of working them
                    the minister of the colonies has commissioned Mr. A. Stoop, an officer of
                    engineers, to visit the United States and Canada, to thoroughly study the
                    methods employed there for such work.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>ISAAC BELL, <hi rend="smallcaps">Jr.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
